<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Front Cover</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; line-height:26pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt; padding-bottom:3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 55 Roman'; font-size:22pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">Written evidence from the Political and </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 55 Roman'; font-size:22pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">Constitutional Reform Committee </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 55 Roman'; font-size:22pt; letter-spacing:-0.5pt">(SCE0004)</span></p><h2 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 10pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction </span></h2><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">This memorandum outlines the work undertaken by the Political and Constitutional Reform Committee (PCRC) since the start of the 2012-13 session.  It supplements the previous memorandum provided to the Liaison Committee in March 2012.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Overall, PCRC has had a busy 18 months, during which it has so far produced 12 reports, as well as holding one-off evidence sessions and seminars, and visiting the devolved Administrations in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland as part of an inquiry into whether there is a need for a constitutional convention for the UK.  The pace of the Government’s programme of political and constitutional reform has slackened somewhat since we last reported to the Liaison Committee, but PCRC has continued to be active, aiming not only to respond to developments, but to set the agenda for future developments.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">We stated in our previous memorandum that for the remainder of the Parliament PCRC’s objectives were:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">to produce an overview of the current UK constitution and a roadmap showing how one would go about codifying it if one wished to do so;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">to maintain its close scrutiny of the Government’s programme of political and constitutional reform; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">to respond to issues of political and constitutional significance as they arise.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">These continue to be our objectives.   </span></p><h2 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 10pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Core tasks </span></h2><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The Liaison Committee’s report on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Select committee effectiveness, resources and powers</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> set out a revised list of core tasks for departmental Select Committees.  PCRC is not a departmental Select Committee—it has a cross-cutting remit “to consider political and constitutional reform”—but it has nonetheless found these core tasks a useful guide when considering and assessing its programme of work.  </span></li></ol><h3 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 9.95pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Strategy</span></h3><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The Government’s programme of political and constitutional reform is the responsibility of the Deputy Prime Minister and mostly falls under the auspices of the Constitution Group in the Cabinet Office.  PCRC holds regular oral evidence sessions with the Deputy Prime Minister, to consider not only policy aims, but the strategy for achieving them.   </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">We have also been considering the Government’s strategy for achieving its aims more widely.  We conducted an inquiry into </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The impact and effectiveness of ministerial reshuffles, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">which concluded that the Government could work more effectively if the Prime Minister kept the number of reshuffles to a minimum.  Our inquiry into </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The role and powers of the Prime Minister: the impact of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011 on Government</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> urged Departments to make more use of the benefits of five-year planning horizons.  It also urged the Government to produce a rolling five-year Spending Review that is more closely aligned to the fixed term in order to maximise these benefits.  </span></li></ol><h3 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 9.95pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Policy</span></h3><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The principal area of Government policy that PCRC has examined over the past 18 months is the proposals for a statutory register of lobbyists.  We produced our initial report, which contained a thorough examination of the proposals in the Government’s consultation paper, on 13 July 2012.  We were extremely disappointed that not only did the Government take more than a year to respond, but, when we finally received a response, on 17 July 2013, it was in the form of a letter, just over one page long, which engaged with none of the detailed points in the original report.  Our report was intended to help the Government refine and develop its proposals.  To respond to it in this way shows a lack of respect for both Parliament and the many people who contributed to our inquiry.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">In other areas, we have been ahead of the game in trying to set the agenda for future policy developments.  For example, our wide-ranging inquiry into </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Prospects for codifying the relationship between central and local government </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">resulted in the publication of a draft code, drawn up by an academic at the request of the Committee, for a new relationship between central and local government.  Our inquiry </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Do we need a constitutional convention for the UK?</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> drew attention to the need to consider the future of the Union as a whole, rather than piecemeal through a focus on specific issues or nations.  When we began the inquiry, few people were discussing whether there was a need for a constitutional convention, but by the time we reported there was much more interest in the matter, as reflected by the press coverage that we received.  </span></li></ol><h3 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 9.95pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Expenditure and performance </span></h3><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Most of the work on the administration and expenditure of the Cabinet Office falls under the remit of the Public Administration Committee.  However, the note prepared for us by the National Audit Office on the expenditure of the Constitution Group within the Cabinet Office will help to inform any future work in this area.  The bulk of the expenditure of the Constitution Group is accounted for by individual electoral registration, which we considered in detail in the 2010-12 session, and on which we held a follow-up evidence session with the Electoral Commission in April 2013.  </span></li></ol><h3 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 9.95pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Draft Bills</span></h3><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">We published our report on the draft Recall of MPs Bill in June 2012.  The report made a number of detailed recommendations for changes to the draft Bill.  We were pleased that the Government’s response accepted nearly all of them and stated:  “The process of pre-legislative scrutiny has been valuable and will result in an improved Bill being presented to Parliament.”  We were, however, frustrated that, having acknowledged the benefits of pre-</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">legislative scrutiny, the Government failed to produce a draft Bill on lobbying for pre-legislative scrutiny, despite indicating that it planned to do so.  Our reports on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Ensuring standards in the quality of legislation </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Revisiting Rebuilding the House: the impact of the Wright reforms</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> both drew attention to the importance of pre-legislative scrutiny.  The latter report argues that it should become mandatory for all Government Bills, except where there is an accepted and pressing need for immediate legislation.  </span></li></ol><h3 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 9.95pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Bills and Delegated Legislation</span></h3><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Instead of publishing a draft lobbying Bill, the Government published the Transparency of Lobbying, Non-Party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Bill on 17 July 2013, one day before the House rose for the summer recess.  Second Reading was scheduled for 3 September, the day after the House returned, and Committee Stage for the following week.  We held an oral evidence session with the Minister on 18 July and issued a call for written evidence.  </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">We then met during the recess to take further oral evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">, and again on 3 September</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">.  We published the evidence in time to inform the de</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">bate on Second Reading and the r</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">eport in</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> time to inform the Committee Stage</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">   Our members tabled amendments to improve the Bill, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">and won concessions from the Government.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">We regret that the Government felt the need to rush this Bill through the House.  While legislation is needed, we can see no reason for the sudden haste, which is particularly striking given that the Government allowed a year to elapse before responding to our initial report.  Allowing us to conduct pre-legislative scrutiny would have resulted in better legislation.  </span></li></ol><h3 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 9.95pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Post-legislative scrutiny </span></h3><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">In July 2013, we published a short report on the impact of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act on Government.  While recognising that it was still “early days”, the report concluded that the introduction of fixed terms had had a beneficial impact on strategic, financial and, above all, legislative planning by Departments.  </span></li></ol><h3 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 9.95pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Appointments</span></h3><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">In July 2013, we held a pre-appointment hearing with the Government’s preferred candidate for the Chair of the House of Lords Appointments Commission.  This was our first pre-appointment hearing since we were set up in 2010.  </span></li></ol><h3 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 9.95pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Support for the House</span></h3><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">We have provided support to inform debates in the House on a number of occasions and in a number of ways.  Our report on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Individual Electoral Registration and Electoral Administration </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">was tagged to Second Reading and Committee Stage proceedings of the Electoral Registration and Administration Bill, and our report on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Introducing a Statutory Register of Lobbyists </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">was tagged to an Opposition day debate on lobbying. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> In addition to tabling amendments to the Transparency of Lobbying</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Non-Party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Bill, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">our members also tabled amendments to the Electoral </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Registration and Administration Bill, with the intention of stimulating debate and ascertaining the Government’s intentions.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">We conducted an inquiry into the impact of the Wright reforms on the House of Commons, which began three years after the Select Committee on the Reform of the House of Commons published its recommendations.  </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Revisiting Rebuilding the House: the impact of the Wright reforms</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> celebrates the positive developments that have resulted from the reforms, but also draws attention to areas where reform is still outstanding, notably the introduction of a House Business Committee, and suggests a way forward.  The Chair launched the report with a statement on the Floor of the House in July 2013.  </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> </span></li></ol><h3 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 9.95pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Public engagement </span></h3><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">As we noted in our previous memorandum to the Liaison Committee, the subject matter with which PCRC is concerned is considered by some to be dry and academic. The need for public engagement, and suggestions for how to interest the public in political and constitutional reform, have formed important elements of some our inquiries, especially the inquiry into whether we need a constitutional convention for the UK.  Our inquiry into </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The prospects for codifying the relationship between central and local government, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">in particular,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">has given rise to some correspondence from members of the public, with which we have been pleased to engage.  We recently started a Twitter account as another method of communicating with members of the public.   </span></li></ol><h2 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 10pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Other achievements and innovations</span></h2><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">As the newest of the Select Committees, we pride ourselves on innovative working methods.  We are particularly keen not to regard the publication of a report as the end of the inquiry process.  To keep the momentum going, we have started to hold a series of post-report follow-up seminars.  The first of these was on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The prospects for codifying the relationship between central and local government</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> and further seminars are planned.  Our initial experience suggests that keeping the numbers of attendees fairly small, and ensuring the Minister is present if possible, are important ways of making the events effective.   Also as part of our follow-up work, the academic who produced for us the draft code for relations between central and local government, is now working on turning the draft code into a Bill.   </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">We continue to work with the Centre for Political and Constitutional Studies at Kings College London, who are supporting our inquiry into </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Mapping the path to codifying—or not codifying—the UK’s constitution.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">  The Centre has already produced two papers for the Committee.  In May 2013, we agreed to a further programme of work, lasting up until the end of the Parliament, which will help us to achieve our first objective of producing</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> an overview of the current UK Constitution and a roadmap showing how one would go about codifying it if one wished to do so</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">We are aware of the Liaison Committee’s report on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Select committee effectiveness, resources and powers, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">and have adopted some of the suggestions it makes.  For example, we have been producing communications plans for new inquiries.  We have also indicated in our reports which recommendations we consider most important and we have distinguished between conclusions and recommendations.  We have, as set out above, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">made use of the opportunity to apply to the Backbench Business Committee for a slot on the Floor of the House to launch a report.  We have noted with interest that some other Committees have held “away days” to discuss their objectives and priorities, and have used professional trainers to help them refresh their questioning skills.  We have not yet done this ourselves, but may wish to do so in the future.  As set out above, we are already making use of outside research, and focusing on following up on reports.</span></li></ol><h2 style="line-height:14.5pt; margin:17pt 0pt 10pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion </span></h2><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">We believe that the effectiveness and value of the work we have done can, as before, be demonstrated by: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The significant amendments that have been made to policy proposals (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Recall of MPs) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">and legislation (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The Government’s lobbying Bill</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">as a result of our work.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The contribution we have made to emerging debates in a number of areas (particularly,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> Prospects for codifying the relationship between central and local government;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Do we need a constitutional convention for the UK?; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> Ensuring standards in the quality of legislation) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">, which is reflected by the press coverage, and by references to the Committee’s reports in work by other Committees (e.g. the House of Lords Constitution Committee), on the Floor of the House, and by think tanks, academics and other individuals.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">PCRC’s establishment as a key player in the field of political and constitutional research and policy making: the Chair, Committee members and staff continue to be invited to participate in external events and key institutions and individuals respond to PCRC’s inquiries.  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:6pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>